(42, 8, 49, 23, 7, 12, 12, 'trouble not the Master', 'Response to Divine Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of human response to divine authority. In both passages, there is a refusal to engage with Godâ€™s power, as seen in the ruler''s message to not trouble Jesus and Ahaz''s declaration to not tempt the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 49, 42, 7, 6, 6, 'trouble not the Master', 'Expressions of Worthiness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of unworthiness in approaching Jesus. In Luke 8:49, the messenger suggests not to trouble Jesus, while in Luke 7:6, the centurion expresses his own unworthiness for Jesus to enter his home.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 49, 40, 9, 23, 26, 'Thy daughter is dead; trouble not the Master.', 'Connection of Healing and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of death and resurrection. In Luke, the announcement of the daughter''s death is made, while in Matthew, Jesus declares she is merely sleeping, leading to her revival. This connection highlights the miraculous power of Jesus over death.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 49, 42, 8, 41, 43, 'Thy daughter is dead', 'Connection of Healing and Death', 'Both passages emphasize the urgency of Jairus'' situation as he seeks healing for his dying daughter. The arrival of the messenger stating, ''Thy daughter is dead,'' underscores the critical moment when hope shifts to despair.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 50, 43, 11, 40, 40, 'believe only', 'Connection of Belief and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the necessity of belief for experiencing divine intervention. In Luke, Jesus assures that belief leads to healing, while in John, He states that belief allows one to witness God''s glory.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 50, 41, 5, 36, 36, NULL, 'Connection of Fear and Belief', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of believing without fear. They convey a similar message to the ruler about maintaining faith in the face of distressing news.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 50, 43, 11, 25, 25, 'believe only', 'Faith and Resurrection', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief leading to life. Both passages emphasize the necessity of faith for healing and resurrection.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 50, 41, 11, 22, 24, 'believe only', 'Connection of Faith and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of belief in achieving desired outcomes. Luke 8:50 speaks of believing for healing, while Mark 11:22-24 discusses believing for the fulfillment of one''s desires.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 50, 42, 8, 48, 48, 'made whole', 'Connection of Faith and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of faith leading to healing. In Luke 8:50, Jesus encourages belief for wholeness, while in Luke 8:48, faith is directly credited with making the woman whole.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 50, 45, 4, 17, 17, 'believe only', 'Faith and Divine Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of belief leading to miraculous outcomes. In Luke, faith is essential for healing, while Romans emphasizes God''s power to bring life from death, underscoring the transformative nature of belief.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 50, 23, 50, 10, 10, 'Fear not: believe only', 'Connection of Faith and Trust', 'This connection highlights the themes of fear and trust in God. Both passages encourage believers to overcome fear through faith, emphasizing the importance of believing and trusting in the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 51, 11, 17, 19, 23, NULL, 'Resurrection of the Dead', 'Both passages emphasize the revival of a child. In Luke, Jesus raises a girl, while Elijah revives a boy in 1 Kings. This connection highlights the theme of divine intervention in restoring life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 51, 12, 4, 4, 6, NULL, 'Isolation and Divine Intervention', 'This connection highlights the theme of isolation before a miraculous event. In both passages, individuals are instructed to enter a closed space, where divine intervention occurs, emphasizing the importance of faith and focus in receiving God''s blessings.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 51, 23, 42, 2, 2, NULL, 'Silence and Selectivity in Ministry', 'This connection highlights the theme of selective engagement in both passages. In Luke, Jesus chooses specific individuals to witness a miracle, while Isaiah emphasizes a quiet demeanor in ministry.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 51, 40, 6, 5, 6, NULL, 'Secrecy in Prayer and Action', 'This connection highlights the theme of exclusivity in both passages. In Luke, only a select few are allowed to witness the miracle, while in Matthew, the emphasis is on private prayer away from public view.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 51, 41, 14, 33, 33, 'Peter, and James, and John', 'Shared Discipleship of Peter, James, John', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Peter, James, and John during significant moments in Jesus'' ministry. Their inclusion highlights their special role among the disciples in witnessing pivotal events.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 51, 42, 9, 28, 28, 'Peter, and James, and John', 'Discipleship and Privilege', 'Both passages emphasize the selectivity of Peter, James, and John in significant moments with Jesus. Their presence in both instances highlights their special role among the disciples.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 51, 41, 5, 37, 40, 'save Peter, and James, and John', 'Disciples Present at Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Peter, James, and John during the healing of the ruler''s daughter. They also highlight the exclusion of others from the house, indicating a selective witnessing of the miracle.', 'parallel', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 52, 42, 23, 27, 27, 'wept, and bewailed', 'Connection of Mourning and Lamentation', 'Both passages emphasize the act of weeping and lamenting. In Luke 8:52, the mourning is for a girl believed to be dead, while in Luke 23:27, the women mourn for Jesus as he approaches crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 52, 43, 11, 4, 4, 'she is not dead, but sleepeth', 'Death and Sleep Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that death is not final. In Luke, Jesus refers to death as sleep, while in John, he states that sickness is not unto death, suggesting a similar theme of hope and restoration.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 52, 1, 23, 2, 2, NULL, 'Death and Mourning', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of mourning for the dead. In Luke, Jesus reassures that the girl is merely sleeping, while in Genesis, Abraham mourns for Sarah''s death. This connection highlights the contrasting perspectives on death and loss.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 52, 1, 27, 34, 35, NULL, 'Connection of Grief and Misunderstanding', 'This connection highlights the theme of misunderstanding surrounding death and loss. In Luke, the crowd''s grief is met with the assertion of life, while in Genesis, Esau''s bitter cry reflects his deep loss and misunderstanding of his father''s blessing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 52, 2, 24, 17, 17, 'she is not dead, but sleepeth', 'Connection of Life and Glory', 'This connection highlights the theme of life and divine presence. In Luke, the phrase ''she is not dead, but sleepeth'' suggests a state of life beyond death, while Exodus describes the ''glory of the Lord'' as a powerful, life-giving force.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 52, 10, 18, 33, 33, 'weep not; she is not dead', 'Expressions of Grief and Mourning', 'Both passages emphasize deep sorrow and mourning. In Luke, the people weep for a girl believed to be dead, while in 2 Samuel, King David mourns for his son Absalom, expressing profound grief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 52, 24, 9, 17, 21, 'Weep not; she is not dead', 'Connection of Mourning and Death', 'This connection highlights the theme of mourning in both passages. In Luke, the response to death is contrasted with the idea of sleep, while Jeremiah calls for mourning women to lament the death and loss in Zion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 53, 23, 53, 3, 3, 'laughed him to scorn', 'Rejection and Scorn Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of being despised and rejected. Both passages emphasize the scorn faced by individuals, with Luke depicting mockery of Jesus and Isaiah describing the rejection of the suffering servant.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 53, 42, 16, 14, 14, 'laughed him to scorn', 'Mockery of Jesus', 'This connection highlights the theme of mockery directed at Jesus. In both passages, individuals respond to Jesus with scorn and derision, reflecting a lack of faith and understanding.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 53, 18, 12, 4, 4, NULL, 'Mockery of the Righteous', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of mockery faced by the righteous. In Luke, the crowd laughs at Jesus, while in Job, the speaker describes being mocked by neighbors despite calling upon God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 8, 53, 18, 17, 2, 2, NULL, 'Mockery in Times of Despair', 'This connection highlights the theme of mockery in moments of suffering. Both passages emphasize the presence of scorn and provocation faced by those in distress.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
